{{Violence against women}}
[[Pregnancy]] is a potential result of [[rape]]. It has been studied in the context of war, particularly [[Forced pregnancy#Forced pregnancy as a means of genocide|as a tool for genocide]], as well as other unrelated contexts, such as rape by a stranger, [[statutory rape]], [[incest]], and [[Teenage pregnancy|underage pregnancy]].  The current [[scientific consensus]] is that rape is as likely as [[consent|consensual]] [[sexual intercourse]] to lead to pregnancy.<ref name=CNN22-08-2012>Dellorto, Danielle (22 August 2012). [http://www.cnn.com/2012/08/21/health/rape-pregnancy/index.html "Experts: Rape does not lower odds of pregnancy"]. [[CNN Health]].</ref><ref name=Reuters-20-08-2012>Begley, Sharon; Heavey, Susan (20 August 2012). [http://news.yahoo.com/rape-trauma-barrier-pregnancy-no-scientific-basis-235231028.html "Rape trauma as barrier to pregnancy has no scientific basis"]. [[Reuters]].</ref>  

Rape can cause difficulties during and after pregnancy, with potential negative consequences for both mother and child.  Medical treatment following a rape includes testing for, preventing, and managing pregnancy.  A woman who becomes pregnant after a rape may face a decision about whether to have an abortion, give the child up for adoption, or raise it.  In some countries where [[abortion]] is illegal even after rape and incest, over 90% of pregnancies in children 15 and under are due to rape by family members.<ref name="Schiffman" />

The false belief that pregnancy can almost never result from rape was widespread for centuries.  In Europe, from medieval times well into the 1700s a man could use a woman's pregnancy as a legal defense to "prove" that he could not have raped her, since her pregnancy was thought to mean that she had enjoyed the sex and therefore consented to it.  In recent decades, several [[pro-life]] politicians and organizations who [[opposition to legal abortion|oppose legal abortion]] in cases of rape have advanced claims that pregnancy very rarely arises from rape, and that the practical relevance of such exceptions to [[abortion law]] is therefore limited or non-existent.<ref name=Clowes97/><ref name=NYT-21-08-2012/><ref name=NJ-21-08-2012/>

== Statistics==
[[File:Christiaen van Couwenbergh - Three Young White Men and a Black Woman - WGA5568.jpg|thumb|''Three Young White Men and a Black Woman'' (1632) by [[Christiaen van Couwenbergh]]. See [[Treatment of slaves in the United States]].]]

Any female capable of [[ovulation]] may become pregnant after rape by a fertile male.  Rape causes tens of thousands of women to become pregnant each year. 
<!-- STUDIES IN THE US -->
In a three-year [[longitudinal study]] of 4,000 American women, physician Melisa Holmes found that forced sexual intercourse causes over 32,000 pregnancies in the United States each year.<ref name="AJOG">{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0002-9378(96)70141-2 |title=Rape-related pregnancy: Estimates and descriptive characteristics from a national sample of women |year=1996 |last1=Holmes |first1=Melisa M. |last2=Resnick |first2=Heidi S. |last3=Kilpatrick |first3=Dean G. |last4=Best |first4=Connie L. |journal=American Journal of Obstetrics and Gynecology |volume=175 |issue=2 |pages=320–4; discussion 324–5 |pmid=8765248}}</ref>  That study revealed that among women aged 12-45, pregnancy occurred in 5% of rapes and 6% of victims{{clarify|date=April 2013|reason=victims of what?}}.<ref name="thornhill">{{cite book |last1=Thornhill |first1=Randy |last2=Palmer |first2=Craig T. |year=2001 |title=[[A Natural History of Rape]]: Biological Bases of Sexual Coercion |publisher=MIT Press |isbn=978-0-262-70083-2 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=xH6v-nB6EegC&printsec=frontcover|page=100}}</ref> A 1987 study also found a 5% pregnancy rate from rape among 18- to 24-year-old higher education students{{clarify|date=April 2013|reason=What definition of higher education? Post-secondary?}} in the US.<ref name="koss1987">{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/0022-006X.55.2.162 |title=The scope of rape: Incidence and prevalence of sexual aggression and victimization in a national sample of higher education students |year=1987 |last1=Koss |first1=Mary P. |last2=Gidycz |first2=Christine A. |last3=Wisniewski |first3=Nadine |journal=Journal of Consulting and Clinical Psychology |volume=55 |issue=2 |pages=162–70 |pmid=3494755}}</ref> A 2005 study placed the rape-related pregnancy rate at around 3–5%.{{sfn|Hazelwood and Burgess|2009|p=28}} Physician Felicia H. Stewart and economist James Trussell estimated that the 333,000 assaults and rapes reported in the US in 1998 caused about 25,000 pregnancies, and up to 22,000 of those pregnancies could have been prevented by prompt medical treatment, such as [[emergency contraception]].<ref name="Stewart">{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0749-3797(00)00243-9 |title=Prevention of pregnancy resulting from rape: A neglected preventive health measure |year=2000 |last1=Stewart |first1=Felicia H |last2=Trussell |first2=James |journal=American Journal of Preventive Medicine |volume=19 |issue=4 |pages=228–9 |pmid=11064225}}</ref> 
<!-- OTHER COUNTRIES -->
A study of [[Ethiopia]]n adolescents who reported being raped found that 17% subsequently became pregnant,<ref name="ReferenceA">{{Cite journal |pmid=10214457 |year=1998 |last1=Mulugeta |first1=E |last2=Kassaye |first2=M |last3=Berhane |first3=Y |title=Prevalence and outcomes of sexual violence among high school students |volume=36 |issue=3 |pages=167–74 |journal=Ethiopian medical journal}}</ref> and rape crisis centres in [[Mexico]] reported the figure the rate of pregnancy from rape at 15–18%.{{sfn|Krug|2002|p=162}}  

Estimates of rape-related pregnancy rates may be low since the crime is under-reported, resulting in some pregnancies from rape not being recorded as such.{{sfn|Hazelwood and Burgess|2009|p=28}}

=== Statutory rape, incest and underage pregnancy ===
{{main|statutory rape|incest|underage pregnancy}}
In 1995–96, the journal ''Family Planning Perspectives'' published a study by the [[Guttmacher Institute]], a sexual health research and policy organization, on [[statutory rape]] (sexual intercourse with a minor) and resulting pregnancies. It drew on other research<ref name="Landry">{{cite journal |first1=David J. |last1=Landry |first2=Jacqueline Darroch |last2=Forrest |title=How Old Are U.S. Fathers? |journal=Family Planning Perspectives |pmid=7589357 |url=http://www.guttmacher.org/pubs/journals/2715995.html |year=1995 |volume=27 |issue=4 |pages=159–61, 165 |doi=10.2307/2136260}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.2105/AJPH.86.4.565 |title=The ages of fathers in California adolescent births, 1993 |year=1996 |last1=Males |first1=Mike |last2=Chew |first2=Kenneth S Y |journal=American Journal of Public Health |volume=86 |issue=4 |pages=565–8 |pmid=8604792 |pmc=1380562}}</ref> to conclude that "at least half of all babies born to minor women are fathered by adult men", and that "although relatively small proportions of 13–14-year-olds have had intercourse, those who become sexually active at an early age are especially likely to have experienced coercive sex: Seventy-four percent of women who had intercourse before age 14 and 60% of those who had sex before age 15 report having had a forced sexual experience". Because of difficulties in bringing such cases to trial, however, "data from the period 1975–1978&nbsp;... indicate that, on average, only 413 men were arrested annually for statutory rape in California, even though 50,000 pregnancies occurred among underage women in 1976 alone."<ref>''Michael M. v. Sonoma County Superior Court'', 450 U.S. 464 (1981).</ref> In that state, it was found that two thirds of babies born to school-age mothers were fathered by adult men.<ref name="Landry" />

<!-- EFFECT OF PRIOR SEXUAL ABUSE ON PREGNANCY-->
Sexual abuse early in life can lead young women to feel a lack of control over their sexual lives, decrease their future likelihood of using [[contraceptive]]s such as condoms, and increase their chances of becoming pregnant or acquiring [[sexually transmitted infections]].{{sfn|Krug|2002|p=162}} A 2007 paper by [[Child Trends]]<ref name="child trends">[http://www.thenationalcampaign.org/resources/pdf/childhood.pdf Childhood sexual abuse and teen pregnancy: a white paper] – Logan ''et al.'', 2007</ref> examined studies from 2000 to 2006 to identify links between sexual abuse and teenage pregnancy, starting with Blinn-Pike et al.'s 2002 [[metastudy]] of 15 studies since 1989.<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Lynn |last1=Blinn-Pike |first2=Thomas |last2=Berger |first3=Diane |last3=Kuschel |first4=Michael |last4=Kaplan |year=2002 |title=Is There a Causal Link between Maltreatment and Adolescent Pregnancy? A Literature Review |journal=Perspectives on Sexual and Reproductive Health |jstor=3030209 |pmid=12043711 |url=http://www.guttmacher.org/pubs/journals/3406802.html |doi=10.2307/3030209 |last5=Kaplan |first5=M |volume=34 |issue=2 |pages=68–75}}</ref> It found that childhood sexual abuse has a "significant association" with adolescent pregnancy. Direct connections have been demonstrated both by retrospective studies examining antecedents to reported pregnancies and prospective studies, which track the lives of sex abuse victims and "can be helpful for determining causality".<ref name="child trends" />{{rp|3}} Eleven cited studies suggested a link and three did not.<ref name="child trends" />{{rp|4}} The more severe forms of abuse, such as rape and incest, entail a greater risk{{clarify|date=April 2013|reason=risk of what?}}.<ref name="child trends" />{{rp|4}}<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S1054-139X(97)00035-9 |title=Ethnic differences in childhood and adolescent sexual abuse and teenage pregnancy |year=1997 |last1=Kenney |first1=Janet W. |last2=Reinholtz |first2=Cindy |last3=Angelini |first3=Patti Jo |journal=Journal of Adolescent Health |volume=21 |pages=3–10 |pmid=9215504 |issue=1}}</ref><ref name="Saewyc">{{cite journal |doi=10.1363/3609804 |title=Teenage Pregnancy and Associated Risk Behaviors Among Sexually Abused Adolescents |year=2004 |last1=Saewyc |first1=Elizabeth M. |last2=Magee |first2=Lara Leanne |last3=Pettingell |first3=Sandra E. |journal=Perspectives on Sexual and Reproductive Health |volume=36 |issue=3 |pages=98–105 |pmid=15306268}}</ref> Although some researchers suggest that pregnancy could be a choice made to escape a "bad situation", it may also be "a direct result of unwanted intercourse", which one study found it to be the case for about 13% of participants in a [[Texas]] parenting program.<ref name="child trends" />{{rp|4}}<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=10494978 |year=1999 |last1=Kellogg |first1=ND |last2=Hoffman |first2=TJ |last3=Taylor |first3=ER |title=Early sexual experiences among pregnant and parenting adolescents |volume=34 |issue=134 |pages=293–303 |journal=Adolescence}}</ref> 

In [[Nicaragua]], between 2000 and 2010, around 172,000 births were recorded for girls under 14&nbsp, representing around 13% of the 1.3 million births attributed to poverty, laws forbidding abortion for rape and incest, poor [[sex education]], lack of access to justice, and beliefs held in the culture and legal system.<ref name="Schiffman">{{cite book |editor1-first=Laura L. |editor1-last=O'Toole |editor2-first=Jessica R. |editor2-last=Schiffman |year=1997 |title=Gender Violence: Interdisciplinary Perspectives |page=235 |isbn=978-0-8147-8041-1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ipsnews.net/2012/08/pregnant-nicaraguan-girls-forced-to-become-mothers/ |title=Pregnant Nicaraguan Girls Forced to Become Mothers |agency=IPS |first=José Adán |last=Silva |date=August 22, 2012 |accessdate=October 21, 2012}}</ref> A 1992 study in [[Peru]] found that 90% of babies delivered to mothers aged 12–16 were conceived through rape, typically by a father, stepfather, or other close relative.<ref name="Schiffman" /><ref>Rosas 1992{{vs|need more bibliographic info|date=October 2012}}</ref> In 1991 in [[Costa Rica]], the figure was similar, with 95% of adolescent mothers under 15 having become pregnant through rape.<ref name="Schiffman" /><ref>Treguear & Carro, 1991{{vs|need more bibliographic info|date=October 2012}}</ref>  

Many of the [[List of youngest birth mothers|youngest documented birth mothers]] in history experienced [[precocious puberty]] and were impregnated as a result of rape, including [[incest]]. The youngest, Peruvian [[Lina Medina]], was impregnated when she was four and had a live birth in 1939, at age five.<ref name="await">{{cite news |last=Brown |first=Elgar |title=American scientists await U.S. visit of youngest mother: Peruvian girl and baby will be exhibited |work=San Antonio Light |date=July 11, 1939 |page=2A}}</ref>

===Pregnancy rate controversy===
There is debate as to whether conception rates are higher from rape or consensual sex.
<!-- HIGHER CONCEPTION RATES --> 
Psychologist Robert L. Smith states that some studies have reported "unusually high rates of conception following rape".<ref name="Smith2005">{{cite book |last1=Smith |first1=Robert L. |year=2005 |chapter=Human sperm competition |editor1-last=Shackelford |editor1-first=Todd K. |editor2-first=Nicholas |editor2-last=Pound |title=Sperm Competition in Humans: Classic and Contemporary Readings |publisher=Taylor & Francis |isbn=978-0-387-28036-3}}{{page needed|date=October 2012}}</ref> He cites a paper by C.A. Fox and Beatrice Fox, reporting that biologist [[Alan Sterling Parkes]] had speculated in personal correspondence that "there is a high conception rate in rape, where hormonal release, due to fear or anger, could produce reflex ovulation".<ref name="fox1971">{{cite journal |doi=10.1530/jrf.0.0240319 |title=A Comparative Study of Coital Physiology, with Special Reference to the Sexual Climax |year=1971 |last1=Fox |first1=C. A. |last2=Fox |first2=B. |journal=Reproduction |volume=24 |issue=3 |pmid=4926898 |pages=319–36}}</ref> Smith also cites veterinary scientist Wolfgang Jöchle, who "proposed that rape may induce ovulaton in human females".<ref name="Jöchle1973">{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/0010-7824(73)90023-1 |title=Coitus-induced ovulation |year=1973 |last1=Jöchle |first1=Wolfgang |journal=Contraception |volume=7 |issue=6 |pages=523–64}}</ref><ref name="Jöchle1975">{{cite journal |pmid=810583 |year=1975 |last1=Jöchle |first1=W |title=Current research in coitus-induced ovulation: A review |issue=22 |pages=165–207 |journal=Journal of reproduction and fertility. Supplement}}</ref> Literary scholar [[Jonathan Gottschall]] and economist Tiffani Gottschall argued in a 2003 ''[[Human Nature (journal)|Human Nature]]'' article that previous studies of rape-pregnancy statistics were not directly comparable to pregnancy rates from consensual intercourse, because the comparisons were largely uncorrected for such factors as the use of [[contraception]]. Adjusting for these factors, they estimated that rapes are about twice as likely to result in pregnancies (7.98%) as "consensual, unprotected penile-vaginal intercourse" (2–4%). They discuss a variety of possible explanations and advance the hypothesis that rapists tend to target victims with biological "cues of high fecundity" and/or subtle indications of ovulation.<ref name=Gottschall03>{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/s12110-003-1014-0 |laysummary=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0812/79895.html |laysource=Politico |laydate=21 August 2012 |title=Are per-incident rape-pregnancy rates higher than per-incident consensual pregnancy rates? |year=2003 |last1=Gottschall |first1=Jonathan A. |last2=Gottschall |first2=Tiffani A. |journal=Human Nature |volume=14 |pages=1–20}}</ref>

<!-- LOWER RATES FROM RAPE -->
In contrast, psychologists Tara Chavanne and Gordon Gallup Jr., citing unpublished dissertations by Rogel and Morgan,<ref name="Rogel1976">{{cite book |last1=Rogel |first1=M. J. |year=1976 |title=Biosocial Aspects of Rape |type=Unpublished Ph.D. dissertation |publisher=Department of Psychology, University of Chicago}}{{page needed|date=October 2012}}</ref><ref name="Morgan1981">{{cite book |last1=Morgan |first1=J. B. |year=1981 |title=Relationship between Rape and Physical Damage During Rape and Phase of Sexual Cycle During Which Rape Occurred |type=Unpublished Ph.D. dissertation |publisher=Department of Educational Psychology, University of Texas at Austin}}{{page needed|date=October 2012}}</ref> argued that female [[adaptation]]s reduce the likelihood of rape during fertile periods.<ref name="Chavanne">{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S1090-5138(98)00016-6 |title=Variation in Risk Taking Behavior Among Female College Students as a Function of the Menstrual Cycle |year=1998 |last1=Chavanne |first1=Tara J |last2=Gallup |first2=Gordon G |journal=Evolution and Human Behavior |volume=19 |pages=27–32}}</ref>  A 1995 study of women who became pregnant after rape found that 60% had been impregnated during consensual intercourse.<ref name="thornhill"/> Anthropologist [[Daniel Fessler]] disputed these findings, saying, "analysis of conception rates reveals that the probability of conception following rape does not differ from that following consensual coitus".<ref name="fessler2003">{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/14616660410001662361 |title=Rape is not less frequent during the ovulatory phase of the menstrual cycle |year=2003 |last1=Fessler |first1=Daniel M.T. |journal=Psychology, Evolution & Gender |volume=5 |issue=3 |pages=127–47}}</ref>

== Rape in war and conflict ==
{{See also|War rape| forced pregnancy| Rape in the Bosnian War|Sexual enslavement by Nazi Germany in World War II}}
[[File:Chinese girl from one of the Japanese Army's 'comfort battalions'.jpg|thumb|185px|[[Forced prostitution]] was used by the Japanese Army during [[World War II]].  [[Rangoon]], [[Myanmar|Burma]]. August 8, 1945. A young [[Chinese diaspora|ethnic Chinese]] woman who was in one of the [[Imperial Japanese Army]]'s "[[Comfort women|comfort battalions]]"  is interviewed by an [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] officer.]]

Rape has been used as a as a weapon of [[psychological warfare]] in war for centuries, to terrorize, humiliate, and undermine the morale of the enemy, and sometimes as an act of [[ethnic cleansing]] to produce babies that share the perpetrators' ethnicity.{{sfn|Carpenter|2007|pp=1–2}} [[Forced pregnancy]], with the intention of forcing the enemy to bear the perpetrators' children, has been noted in places including [[Bangladesh]], [[Darfur]], and [[Bosnia]].{{sfn|Carpenter|2007|p=2}} More broadly, pregnancy commonly results from wartime rape that was perpetrated without the intention of impregnating the enemy, as has been found in conflicts in [[East Timor]], [[Liberia]], [[Kosovo]], and [[Rwanda]].{{sfn|Carpenter|2007|p=2}}  [[Gita Sahgal]] of [[Amnesty International]] commented that, rather than being primarily about "spoils of war" or sexual gratification, rape is often used in ethnic conflicts as a way for attackers to perpetuate social control and redraw ethnic boundaries.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/low/in_depth/4078677.stm |title=In Depth &#124; How did rape become a weapon of war? |publisher=BBC News |date=8 December 2004 |accessdate=4 March 2010 | first=Laura | last=Smith-Spark}}</ref> Children may be born to women and girls forced to "marry" abductors and occupiers; this happened in the [[Indonesian occupation of East Timor]] and in the [[Lord's Resistance Army|Lord's Resistance Army's]] conflict in [[Uganda]].{{sfn|Carpenter|2007|p=5, 94–95}}

Pregnancy from rape is recognized under the Geneva Convention as a [[crime against humanity]] and [[war crime]].<ref name="britannica.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/facts/5/877066/Geneva-Conventions-as-discussed-in-rape-crime |title=Geneva Conventions as Discussed in Rape Crime |publisher=Britannica.com |date= |accessdate=2012-09-07}}</ref> 

<!-- CHILDREN OF WAR RAPE -->
Children born as the result of wartime rape may be identified with the enemy and grow up stigmatized and excluded by their communities; they may be denied basic rights or even killed before reaching adulthood.{{sfn|Carpenter|2007|p=2}} Children are particularly at risk for such abuse when they are visibly identifiable as sharing half their ethnicity with the occupying forces, as in the case of half-Arab children of Darfuri women raped by [[janjaweed]] soldiers as part of the [[war in Darfur]].{{sfn|Carpenter|2007|p=5}}  Children of war rape are also at risk due to neglect by traumatized mothers unable to provide sufficient care.{{sfn|Carpenter|2007|p=5}}

=== Rape of Nanking ===
In 1937 the Japanese army took over [[Nanking]], which at the time was the capital of China. In the resulting seven-week occupation known as the [[Rape of Nanking]], as many as 80,000 people were raped.{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=194–5}} Chinese women and girls of all ages were raped, mutilated, tortured, sexually enslaved, and killed; unknown numbers of them were left pregnant.{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=194–5}} Many pregnant Nanking women killed themselves in 1938, and others committed [[infanticide]] when their babies were born.{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=194–5}} During the rest of the 20th century there was no record of any Chinese woman acknowledging her child as having been born as a result of the Rape of Nanking.{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=194–5}}

=== Bosnian War ===
During the 1992–95 [[Bosnian War]], pregnancy from rape was used to perpetrate [[genocide]].  There were reports of deliberately created "rape camps" intended to impregnate captive Muslim and Croatian women. Women were reported to have been kept in confinement until their pregnancies had advanced beyond a stage at which [[abortion]] would be safe.{{sfn|Hazelwood and Burgess|2009|p=34}} In the context of a [[Patrilineality|patrilineal]] society, in which children inherit their father's ethnicity, such camps were intended to create a new generation of Serbian children.{{sfn|Hazelwood and Burgess|2009|p=34}} The women's group ''Tresnjevka'' claimed that more than 35,000 women and children were held in such Serb-run camps.<ref name="Tresnjevka">{{cite book |last= de Brouwer |first=Anne-Marie |title= Supranational Criminal Prosecution of Sexual Violence |url=http://books.google.com/?id=JhY8ROsA39kC&dq=war+rape+in+ancient+times |publisher=Intersentia |isbn=90-5095-533-9 |pages=9–10 |year=2005 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.newint.org/issue244/rape.htm new Internationalist] issue 244, June 1993. Rape: Weapon of War by Angela Robson.</ref><ref>[http://hrw.org/english/docs/2001/02/22/bosher256.htm Human Rights News ''Bosnia: Landmark Verdicts for Rape, Torture, and Sexual Enslavement: Criminal Tribunal Convicts Bosnian Serbs for Crimes Against Humanity''] 22 February 2001</ref> Estimates range from 20,000<ref>[http://ocw.mit.edu/NR/rdonlyres/Anthropology/21A-217Fall-2004/BC205381-420D-471A-8B40-2AF7FFA4B0C0/0/6_yugoslavia.pdf Massachusetts Institute of Tehnology-short time line of Yugoslav war with number of rapes]{{dead link|date=September 2012}}</ref> to 50,000<ref>The Independent (London): Film award forces Serbs to face spectre of Bosnia's rape babies – [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20060220/ai_n16146172]</ref> victims.<ref>{{cite web|author=Aldi, Halilovic |url=http://www.odjek.ba/index.php?broj=03&id=21 |title=Odjek – revija za umjetnost i nauku – Zločin silovanja u BiH |publisher=Odjek.ba |date=2000-12-21 |accessdate=2012-09-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coop99.at/grbavica_website/ |title=Grbavica (film) |publisher=Coop99.at |date= |accessdate=2012-09-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.un.org/icty/krnojelac/appeal/judgement/index.htm |title=ICTY: Krnojelac verdict |publisher=Un.org |date=2007-03-05 |accessdate=2012-09-07}}</ref>  Feryal Gharahi of [[Equality Now]] reported:

: "Families were separated, and women and children were kept in the gym, where all of the women and girls over ten years old were raped in the first few days.... There are rape camps all over the country. Thousands of women are being raped and killed. Thousands of women are pregnant as a result of rape. Over and over again, everywhere I went in Bosnia-Herzegovina and in Croatian refugee camps, women told me stories of abomination – of being kept in a room, raped repeatedly and told they would be held until they gave birth to Serbian children."&nbsp;<ref name="Gharahi">{{cite web |url= http://www.equalitynow.org/take_action/bosnia_herzegovina_action31 |title=Bosnia-Herzegovina: Mass Rape, Forced Pregnancy, Genocide|first= Feryal|last=Gharahi |work= [[Equality Now]] |year=1 Feb 1993|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref>

After the Bosnian War, the [[International Criminal Court]] updated its statute to prohibit "confin[ing] one or more women forcibly made pregnant, with the intent of affecting the ethnic composition of any population".{{sfn|de Brouwer|2005|p=145}}

== Sociobiology ==
{{main|Sociobiological theories of rape}}
[[Sociobiologists]] and [[evolutionary psychology|evolutionary psychologists]] have hypothesized that causing pregnancy by rape may be a [[mating strategy]] in humans, as a way for males to ensure the survival of their genes by passing them on to future generations.<ref name="mckibbin">{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/1089-2680.12.1.86 |title=Why do men rape? An evolutionary psychological perspective |year=2008 |last1=McKibbin |first1=William F. |last2=Shackelford |first2=Todd K. |last3=Goetz |first3=Aaron T. |last4=Starratt |first4=Valerie G. |journal=Review of General Psychology |volume=12 |pages=86–97}}</ref> Randy Thornhill and [[Craig T. Palmer]] are key popularizers of this hypothesis. They assert that most rape victims are women of childbearing age and that many cultures treat rape as a crime against the victim’s husband. They state that rape victims suffer less emotional distress when they are subjected to more violence, and that married women and women of childbearing age experience less psychological distress after a rape than do girls, single women or post-menopausal women.<ref name="thornhill2000">{{cite journal |last1=Thornhill |first1=Randy |last2=Palmer |first2=Craig T |year=2000 |title=Why men rape |journal=Sciences |volume=40 |issue=1 |pages=30–6 |issn=0036-861X |oclc=93004665}}</ref>  Rape-pregnancy rates are crucial in evaluating these theories, because a high or low pregnancy rate from rape would determine whether such adaptations are favored or disfavored by [[natural selection]].<ref name=Gottschall03/>

== Treatment and outcomes==
Immediate post-rape treatment protocols call for medical professionals to assess the likelihood that a victim will become pregnant and obtain a history of the use of contraceptives, as a woman's use of [[birth control pills]] or other contraceptives before a rape affect her chance of becoming pregnant.{{sfn|Krug|2002|pp=162, 166}}  Treatment protocols also call for clinicians to provide access to [[emergency contraception]] and counseling on abortion in countries where it is legal.{{sfn|Krug|2002|p=166}}  High-dose estrogen pills were tried as an experimental treatment after rape in the 1960s, and in 1972 Canadian physician [[A. Albert Yuzpe]] and his colleagues began systematic studies on the use of [[ethinyl estradiol]] and [[dl-norgestrel]] to provide emergency contraception after an assault.<ref name="yuzpe">{{cite journal |pmid=7040117 |year=1982 |last1=Yuzpe |first1=AA |last2=Smith |first2=RP |last3=Rademaker |first3=AW |title=A multicenter clinical investigation employing ethinyl estradiol combined with dl-norgestrel as postcoital contraceptive agent |volume=37 |issue=4 |pages=508–13 |journal=Fertility and sterility}}</ref> This method is now called the [[Yuzpe regimen]].<ref name="Haspels">{{cite journal |pmid=7956209 |year=1994 |last1=Haspels |first1=AA |title=Emergency contraception: A review |volume=50 |issue=2 |pages=101–8 |journal=Contraception |doi=10.1016/0010-7824(94)90046-9}}</ref>  Before being treated with pregnancy prevention measures, a rape victim is given a [[human chorionic gonadotropin|HCG]] [[pregnancy test]] to determine whether she was already pregnant before the rape.{{sfn|Jenkins and Braen|2004|p=311}} 

When being discharged from emergency care, clinicians provide information about pregnancy as well as other complications such as infection and emotional trauma.{{sfn|Jenkins and Braen|2004|p=311}} Followup care is also needed, including a gynecological referral, and return visits should occur at two and six weeks after the rape, as well as any occasion when the patient feels she needs to return for emergency care.{{sfn|Jenkins and Braen|2004|pp=311–312}}  While a woman raped within 48 hours will test negative for pregnancy in an HCG pregnancy test (unless she was already pregnant before the rape), pregnancy resulting from the rape can be detected at the two-week followup visit.{{sfn|Jenkins and Braen|2004|pp=311–312}}

Decisions of whether to end a rape-related pregnancy or carry it to term, and whether to keep the child or give it up for adoption can be severely traumatizing for a woman.{{sfn|de Brouwer|2005|p=225}} 
