ABORTION STATISTICS -->
[[Abortion]] rates for pregnancies due to rape vary significantly by culture and demographics; women who live in countries where abortion is illegal must often give birth to the child or secretly undergo a dangerous, [[unsafe abortion|back-alley abortion]].{{sfn|Krug|2002|p=162}}  Some women do not wish to get abortions for religious or cultural reasons.{{sfn|Price|2007|p=173}}  In a third of cases, rape-related pregnancies are not discovered until the second [[trimester of pregnancy]], often leaving the woman pressed for time in which to make a weighty decision about whether to have an abortion within the time frame in which the procedure is safe.<ref name=Solomon2012>{{cite web|last=Solomon |first=Andrew |url=http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/newsdesk/2012/08/the-legitimate-children-of-rape.html |title=The Legitimate Children of Rape |publisher=The New Yorker |date=August 29, 2012 |accessdate=2013-02-19}}</ref>
<!-- 
BIRTH STATISTICS -->
A 1996 study of thousands of US women showed that, of pregnancies resulting from rape, 12% resulted in [[miscarriage]], and 50% were [[medical abortion|aborted]], and 38% were brought to term and either given up for adoption or raised.<ref name="thornhill"/>  Peer-reviewed studies have reported from 38% of American women to 90% of Peruvian adolescents carrying the pregnancy to term.<ref name="AJOG"/><ref name="tobach"/> In [[Lima, Peru]], where abortion is illegal, 90% of girls aged 12 to 16 who became pregnant through rape carried the child to term.<ref name="tobach">{{cite book |last1=Tobach |first1=Ethel |last2=Reed |first2=Rachel |year=2003 |chapter=Understanding rape |editor1-first=Cheryl Brown |editor1-last=Travis |title=Evolution, Gender, and Rape |publisher=MIT Press |isbn=978-0-262-70090-0}}{{page needed|date=October 2012}}</ref>
<!--
ADOPTION STATISTICS -->
Of all children born, 1% are put up for adoption; the number of children conceived from rape who are given up for adoption was found to be about 6% in one study and 26% in another.<ref name=Palmer2012/>    
<!-- INFANTICIDE -->
When a mother commits [[neonaticide]], killing an infant younger than 24 hours old, the child's birth being the result of rape is a main cause, although other psychological and situational factors are generally present.<ref name="Hickey2003">{{cite book
|author=Eric W. Hickey
|title=Encyclopedia of Murder and Violent Crime
|chapter = Child killing
|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=dDOW75aJMR8C&pg=PA389
|accessdate=14 February 2013
|date=22 July 2003
|publisher=SAGE
|isbn=978-0-7619-2437-1
|pages=78–80}}</ref>

Some people turn to drugs or alcohol to cope with emotional trauma after a rape; use of these during pregnancy can harm the fetus.{{sfn|Price|2007|p=151–152}}

== Children of rape ==
<!-- RAISING THE CHILD -->
For a mother who raises a rape-conceived child, both the traumatic effect of the rape and the child's blood relationship to the rapist can create significant psychological problems for both mother and child.<ref name=Palmer2012>{{cite web |last=Palmer |first=Brian |title=Should a Mother Tell Her Child He Was Conceived in a Rape? |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/explainer/2012/08/rape_and_pregnancy_is_it_best_to_tell_a_child_he_was_conceived_in_a_rape_.html |work=Slate |date=22 August 2012 |accessdate=29 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=prewitt/>  
If a woman decides to keep and raise the child, she may have difficulty accepting it, and both mother and child face societal ostracism in some societies.{{sfn|de Brouwer|2005|p=144}}

<!-- LEGAL ISSUES -->
Mothers may also face legal difficulties.  In most US states, the rapist maintains parental rights.<ref name=prewitt/> Research by legal scholar Shauna Prewitt indicates that the resulting continued contact with the rapist is damaging for women who keep the child.<ref name=prewitt>{{cite journal |last1=Prewitt |first1=Shauna R. |year=2010 |title=Giving Birth to a 'Rapist's Child': A Discussion and Analysis of the Limited Legal Protections Afforded to Women Who Become Mothers Through Rape |journal=Georgetown Law Journal |volume=98 |issue=3 |pages=831–62 |url=http://georgetownlawjournal.org/articles/giving-birth-to-a-rapists-child-a-discussion-and-analysis-of-the-limited-legal-protections-afforded-to-women-who-become-mothers-through-rape/}}</ref>  She wrote in 2012 that in the US, 31 states allow rapists to assert custody and visitation rights over children conceived through rape.<ref name="prewitt">Prewitt, Shauna (August 22, 2012). [http://www.cnn.com/2012/08/22/opinion/prewitt-rapist-visitation-rights/index.html Raped, pregnant and ordeal not over.] [[CNN]]</ref>

== History ==
Children whose births result from rape have been killed by their mothers at various times in history; during ancient and medieval times, such [[infanticide]] was not prohibited (however [[penance]] was expected of these mothers in medieval Europe).<ref name=Solomon2012/>

=== Law ===
In contrast to the modern scientific consensus that rape-induced pregnancies are no less likely than any other, beliefs that rape could not lead to pregnancy were widespread in both legal and medical opinion for centuries.<ref name=Heggie12/><ref name=Tucker-NYT-23-08-2012/>  [[Galen]], an ancient Greek physician, believed that a woman must experience pleasure to release "seed" and become pregnant, and could not derive such pleasure from nonconsensual sex.{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=155}}  Galen's thinking influenced understanding from medieval England to [[Colonial America]].{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=155}}  

[[File:Galen detail.jpg|thumb|left|The Ancient Greek physician [[Galen|Galen's]] belief that women could not conceive without pleasure influenced medical and legal thinking for centuries.]]
The Ancient Greek philosopher [[Aristotle]] also believed that female pleasure played a central role in conception.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}} Female reproduction was, in many ways, viewed through the lens of male reproductive processes, imagining that female organs functioned as inverted versions of male organs, and hence orgasm was required for conception.<ref name=Heggie12/>

Centuries later, in medieval Europe, the belief that pregnancy could not occur without consent was still standard; in fact, conception by a woman was considered a legitimate defense against charges of rape.<ref name=Tucker-NYT-23-08-2012/> The belief was codified in the medieval British law texts ''[[Fleta]]''<ref name=Heggie12/> and ''[[Britton (law)|Britton]]''. ''Britton'' states:

<blockquote>If the defendant confesses the fact, but says that the woman at the same time conceived by him, and can prove it, then our will is that it be adjudged no felony, because no woman can conceive if she does not consent.<ref name="Nichols1865"/></blockquote>

Medieval literary scholar Corinne Saunders acknowledged a difficulty in determining how widely held was the belief that pregnancy implies consent, but concluded that it influenced "at least some justices", citing a 1313 case in Kent.<ref name="Saunders">Saunders, Corinne J. (2001). ''Rape and Ravishment in the Literature of Medieval England.'' D. S. Brewer, ISBN 978-0-85991-610-3</ref>

By the late 1700s, scientists no longer universally accepted the view that pregnancy was impossible without pleasure, although this view was still common.{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=2–3}} A 1795 British legal text, ''[[Hawkins' Treatise of Pleas of the Crown|Treatise of Pleas of the Crown]]'', disparaged the belief's legal utility and its biological veracity:

<blockquote>Also it hath been said by some to be no rape to force a woman who conceives at the time; for it is said, that if she had not consented, she could not have conceived, but this opinion seems very questionable, not only because the previous violence is no way extenuated by such a subsequent consent, but also because, if it were necessary to shew that the woman did not conceive, the offender could not be tried till such time as it might appear whether she did or did not...<ref name=Tucker-NYT-23-08-2012/><ref>William Hawkins, [http://books.google.com/books?id=hLBCAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA308&lpg=PA308 Treatise of Pleas of the Crown], seventh edition, p. 308 (London, 1795).</ref></blockquote>

The 1814 British legal text ''Elements of Medical Jurisprudence'' by [[Samuel Farr (physician)|Samuel Farr]] claimed that conception "probably" could not occur without a woman's "enjoyment", so that an "absolute rape" was unlikely to lead to pregnancy.<ref name=Heggie12/><ref>Samuel Farr, [http://books.google.com/books?id=vTeHRzdCpJwC&lpg=PA25&ots=-ON8tpZavp&dq=%22So%20that%20if%20an%20absolute%20rape%20were%20to%20be%22&pg=PA25 Elements of Medical Jurisprudence], second edition, chapter IV (London, 1814). See also [https://play.google.com/store/books/details?id=i1cOAAAAQAAJ&rdid=book-i1cOAAAAQAAJ&rdot=1 scanned original book].</ref> On the other hand, in the US, in an 1820 court case in the [[Arkansas Territory]], a man plead innocent to rape charges because the victim became pregnant, but the court rejected the argument:

<blockquote>The old notion that if the woman conceive, it could not be a rape, because she must have in such case have consented, is quite exploded.  Impregnation, it is well known, does not depend on the consciousness or volition of the female. If the uterine organs be in a condition favorable to impregnation, this may take place as readily as if the intercourse was voluntary."<ref name="U.S. v. Dickinson, 1 Hempstead Reporter 1 (1820 Ark. Territory), at 2 n.1.">{{cite book|title=U.S. v. Dickinson, 1 Hempstead Reporter 1 (1820 Ark. Territory), at 2 n.1.|url=http://books.google.com/?id=VFowAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA2&lpg=PA2&dq=%22If+the+uterine+organs+be+in+a+condition+favorable%22#v=onepage&q=%22If%20the%20uterine%20organs%20be%20in%20a%20condition%20favorable%22&f=false|author1=Hempstead|first1=Samuel H|last2=Circuit Court (9Th Circuit)|first2=United States|last3=Superior Court|first3=Arkansas|last4=District Court (Arkansas)|first4=United States|year=1856}}</ref></blockquote>

==== Islamic law ====
Historian Ian Talbot has written about how countries with [[Quran]]-based [[Sharia|Islamic codes]] on rape and pregnancy use Sura [[An-Nur]], verse 2, as a legal basis: "The law of evidence in all sexual crimes required either self-confession or the testimony of four upright (''salah'') Muslim males. In the case of a man, self-confession involved a verbal confession. For women however medical examinations and pregnancy arising from rape were admissible as proof of self-guilt."<ref name="Talbot">Talbot Ian (1998). ''Pakistan: A Modern History.'' Palgrave Macmillan. p. 276. ISBN 978-0-312-21606-1</ref>

== Opposition to legal abortion ==
{{See also|Rape and pregnancy controversies in United States elections, 2012}}
Pregnancy from rape is an [[ethics|ethical]] and [[morality|moral]] issue in the context of [[opposition to legal abortion]]. In recent decades, claims of the improbability of rape-induced pregnancy, reminiscent of historical beliefs,<ref name=Reuters-20-08-2012/><ref name=Heggie12/> have again begun to play a role in political discourse surrounding abortion regulation in cases of rape.<ref name=Reuters-20-08-2012/><ref name=NJ-21-08-2012>Garance Franke-Ruta, [http://www.nationaljournal.com/politics/analysis-a-canard-that-will-not-die-legitimate-rape-doesn-t-cause-pregnancy-20120820 Analysis — A Canard That Will Not Die: 'Legitimate Rape' Doesn't Cause Pregnancy], ''[[National Journal]]'' (21 August 2012).</ref>

Claims that rape reduces the chance of pregnancy have at times been made by referring to the established medical fact that [[chronic stress]] can reduce a woman's fertility over a long term, but the current scientific consensus is that this is specific to long-term stress—the [[acute stress reaction]] that occurs during rape cannot "shut down ovulation that has already begun".<ref name=CNN22-08-2012/><ref name=Reuters-20-08-2012/>  In a 1972 article, physician [[Fred Mecklenburg]] argued that pregnancy from rape is "extremely rare", adding that a woman exposed to the trauma of rape "will not [[ovulate]] even if she is 'scheduled' to".<ref name="Mecklenburg">Mecklenburg, Fred E. (1972). The Indications for Induced Abortion: A Physician's Perspective. In ''Abortion and Social Justice'', Thomas Hilgers and Dennis Horan, eds., p. 50. Sheed & Ward, ISBN 978-0-8362-0542-8</ref>  Blythe Bernhard wrote in ''[[The Washington Post]]'', "That article has influenced two generations of anti-abortion activists with the hope to build a medical case to ban all abortions without any exception."<ref name="Bernhard2012">Bernhard, Blythe (August 22, 2012). [http://www.washingtonpost.com/national/on-faith/the-roots-of-rep-todd-akins-legitimate-rape-remarks/2012/08/22/5c69929c-ec95-11e1-866f-60a00f604425_story.html The roots of Rep. Todd Akin’s “legitimate” rape remarks.] ''[[Washington Post]]''</ref> [[J. C. Willke|John C. Willke]], a former president of the [[National Right to Life Committee]] and a general practitioner with training in obstetrics, has published similar statements since 1985.<ref name=NYT-21-08-2012/><ref name=NJ-21-08-2012/> In a 2012 interview he said, "This is a traumatic thing&nbsp;– she's, shall we say, she's uptight. She is frightened, tight, and so on. And sperm, if deposited in her vagina, are less likely to be able to fertilize. The tubes are spastic." These assertions were disputed by a number of gynecology professors.<ref name=NYT-21-08-2012>{{cite news | title = Health Experts Dismiss Assertions on Rape | date = 2012-08-21 | url = http://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/21/us/politics/rape-assertions-are-dismissed-by-health-experts.html | work = The New York Times | accessdate = 2012-08-21}}</ref> A 1997 book published by the group [[Human Life International]] (which opposes legal abortion in all cases, including rape) claims that several studies performed in the 1970s show that only 0.08% of rapes result in pregnancy, and alternatively offers an estimate of 0.8% from other data. The same book dismisses contrary statistics, claiming that "the women who obtain abortions for 'rape' are almost always lying".<ref name=Clowes97>Brian Clowes, ''The Facts of Life: An Authoritative Guide to Life & Family Issues'', [http://www.hli.org/index.php/cloning/685?task=view Chapter 3: Exceptions for Abortion: The Frequency of Rape-Caused Pregnancies] (Human Life International, 1997).  ISBN 978-1-55922-043-9.</ref> 

Related views have also been expressed by pro-life groups outside the United States.  The [[United Kingdom]] pro-life group [[Society for the Protection of Unborn Children]] similarly claims that rape-pregnancy is "extremely rare", in part because the "trauma of being raped makes it difficult for fertilisation or implantation to occur".<ref>[http://www.spuc.org.uk/youth/student_info_on_abortion/rape Abortion after rape], ''Society for the Protection of Unborn Children'' web site, accessed 23 August 2012.</ref>  The Irish pro-life group [[Youth Defence]] published claims on its web site that "trauma from the rape may bring into play some natural defence mechanisms that reduce the likelihood of pregnancy", but removed these statements in 2012 following the Akin controversy, explaining that the group now deemed them "unreliable".<ref>Pope, Conor. [http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2012/0823/1224322768272.html Group removes claims on rape], ''[[The Irish Times]]'' (23 August 2012).</ref>  The Irish group [[Precious Life (organisation)|Precious Life]] published claims that "the trauma of sexual assault is likely to inhibit ovulation" and "the rate of pregnancy arising from sexual assault is 0.1%".<ref>[http://www.preciouslife.com/fulds/49.pdf Women have a right to know], [http://www.preciouslife.com/?va=20&vb=30 Precious Life Publications], accessed 28 August 2012.</ref> Other groups that say rape prevents ovulation include the Australian group ''Pro-Life Victoria'',<ref>Carolyn Gerstner, "[http://www.prolife.org.au/articles/abortion_anti-abortion_theology/article_18.php Why not keep legalized abortion for rape and incest?], ''Pro-Life Victoria'' web site, accessed 27 August 2012.</ref> and the group ''Pro-Life Philippines''.<ref>[http://2011.prolife.org.ph/?page_id=231 Abortion in woman’s dilemma], ''Pro-life Philippines Foundation, Inc.'', accessed 30 August 2012.</ref>  The [[Austria]]n group ''Jugend für das Leben'' (Youth for Life) writes that "pregnancies after rape are extremely rare" because "protective mechanisms" from the stress of rape will "almost always prevent conception".<ref>[http://www.youthforlife.net/abortion.php Youth for Life web page] (English version), accessed 28 August 2012.</ref> 

Several US Republican politicians have advanced claims that pregnancy from rape is rare. Pennsylvania state representative [[Stephen Freind]] claimed in 1988 that the odds of a pregnancy resulting from rape were "one in millions and millions and millions".<ref>{{cite news|last=Kliff |first=Sarah |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/ezra-klein/wp/2012/08/20/rep-todd-akin-is-wrong-about-rape-and-pregnancy-but-hes-not-alone/ |title=Rep. Todd Akin is wrong about rape and pregnancy, but he’s not alone |publisher=The Washington Post |date=August 20, 2012 |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Freind admits he erred, exaggerated on rapes|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=n9RRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8m0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=3152,8910888&dq=stephen+freind+one+in+millions+and+millions+and+millions&hl=en|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=March 30, 1988}}</ref> [[James Leon Holmes]] published a letter in 1980 stating, "concern for rape victims is a red herring because conceptions from rape occur with approximately the same frequency as snowfall in Miami".<ref name=WP-06-07-2004/> Holmes apologized for this remark in 2003 after he was nominated as a [[United States federal judge]]. (He was confirmed in 2004).<ref name=WP-06-07-2004>Charles Babington, [http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A32206-2004Jul6.html Senate Confirms Controversial Nominee to Federal Court], ''Washington Post'' (7 July 2004).</ref><ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=FtNW4skCGBUC&pg=PA14334&lpg=PA14334 Congressional Record] of the US Senate, v. 150, p. 14334 (6 July 2004).</ref> In 1995, [[North Carolina House of Representatives]] member [[Henry Aldridge]] remarked during a debate to eliminate a state abortion fund for poor women: "The facts show that people who are raped&nbsp;– who are truly raped&nbsp;– the juices don't flow, the body functions don't work and they don't get pregnant. Medical authorities agree that this is a rarity, if ever."<ref>{{cite news|title=N.C. Legislator Says Rape Victims Don't Get Pregnant|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=5eU_AAAAIBAJ&sjid=X1gMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6720,2257940&dq=victims-don-t-get-pregnant&hl=en|newspaper=The Mount Airy News|date=April 21, 1995}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = A Canard That Will Not Die: 'Legitimate Rape' Doesn't Cause Pregnancy | date = 19 Aug 2012 | url = http://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2012/08/a-canard-that-will-not-die-legitimate-rape-doesnt-cause-pregnancy/261303/ | work = The Atlantic | accessdate = 2012-08-21}}</ref> In 1998, Arkansas state senator [[Fay Boozman]] lost a campaign for a US Senate seat after remarking that fear-induced hormonal changes made rape victims unlikely to become pregnant. He later apologized and eventually called the claim a mistake, but the controversy was renewed in 1999 when he was appointed director of the Arkansas Department of Health by then-governor [[Mike Huckabee]].<ref>"Boozman says rape remark a mistake", ''Associated Press'' (15 February 1999).</ref><ref>Louise Radnofsky, [http://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2012/08/21/fates-of-past-lawmakers-after-rape-remarks/ Fates of Past Lawmakers After Rape Remarks], ''Washington Wire'', ''Wall Street Journal'' blogs (21 August 2012).</ref> During his campaign in the [[United States Senate election in Missouri, 2012]], US Representative [[Todd Akin rape and pregnancy controversy|Todd Akin commented]] on abortion exceptions for rape victims: "I understand from doctors, that's really rare. If it's a legitimate rape, the female body has ways to try to shut that whole thing down."<ref>{{cite web|last=Jaco|first=Charles|title=The Jaco Report: August 19, 2012|url=http://fox2now.com/2012/08/19/the-jaco-report-august-19-2012/|publisher=Fox News|accessdate=20 August 2012}}</ref></blockquote> The comment was widely criticized,<ref>{{cite web|last=DiSalvo|first=David|title=Republican Senate Nominee Todd Akin: Victims Of "Legitimate Rape" Don't Get Pregnant|url=http://www.forbes.com/sites/daviddisalvo/2012/08/19/republican-senate-nominee-todd-akin-victims-of-legitimate-rape-dont-get-pregnant/|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=20 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Abouhalkah|first=Yael T.|title=Todd Akin's rape fantasy|url=http://voices.kansascity.com/entries/todd-akins-rape-fantasy/|publisher=Kansas City Star|accessdate=20 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Eligon|first=John|title=Senate Candidate Provokes Ire With ‘Legitimate Rape’ Comment|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/20/us/politics/todd-akin-provokes-ire-with-legitimate-rape-comment.html|accessdate=20 August 2012}}</ref><ref>Hilary Whiteman [http://www.cnn.com/2012/08/22/world/akin-international-rape-reaction/index.html Akin 'legitimate rape' reaction, from the Congo to black crickets], ''CNN World'' (22 August 2012).</ref><ref>Editorial, [http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/314502/step-aside-todd-akin-editors Step Aside, Todd Akin], ''National Review'' (20 August 2012).</ref> and Akin apologized, saying he "misspoke". Akin's suggestion that rape might impede pregnancy was defended by some prominent individuals and groups which oppose legal abortion.<ref name=NYT-21-08-2012/><ref>de Solenni, Pia. "[http://piadesolenni.com/when-pro-lifers-do-the-work-for-abortion-advocates/ Responding To Akin: When Pro-Lifers Do The Work For Abortion Advocates]", blog posting (21 August 2012).</ref><ref>Fleischmann, Robert. [http://www.christianliferesources.com/news/rape-pregnancy-and-the-akin-controversy-8741 Rape, Pregnancy, and the Akin Controversy], Christian Life Resources (21 August 2012).</ref> A [[SurveyUSA]] poll one day after Akin's comments reported that 13% of Missouri adults agreed with Akin's statement and 11% were unsure ([[sampling error|±3.8%]]).<ref>[http://www.surveyusa.com/client/PollReport.aspx?g=be5d9bf6-7675-4341-920a-8fcb71d9e9de SurveyUSA News Poll #19525], performed 20 August 2012.  Accessed 28 August 2012.</ref>

